answers.body_markdown:
`^` is the [bitwise xor operator][1]. It doesn&#39;t calculate powers.

To calculate y^2, you could either write `y*y` or use `Math.pow(y,2)`. However note that in case `y` is an int, `y*y` will return an `int`, but `Math.pow()` will return a double.

And one more thing - you can&#39;t assign a value to `x^2`. You can only assign a value to `x`.

Hence, to calculate x, we need something like this:

	int y = 3;
	int z = 4;

	double x = Math.sqrt(y * y + z * z);
	System.out.println(x);  //x will be equal to 5.0

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/operators.html

Either use Math.pow(x,2) or use x*x to get x^2

you can form the logic on that line.

For the question you asked, try 


    double x = Math.sqrt(Math.pow(y,2)+Math.pow(z,2);
    System.out.println(Math.pow(x,2));

